                <h1>Run Processes in Background: The & Metacharacter Explained</h1>
                <p>To run a process in the background in a Unix-like operating system, the metacharacter used is the ampersand (&). By appending & to a command, you initiate the process without tying up the terminal, allowing you to continue executing other commands. This is particularly useful for multitasking in the command-line interface.</p>
